  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: f4688fdb7df04437aeb418b961361dc5, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Unity.TextMeshPro::TMPro.TextMeshProUGUI
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "The Obalufon Ogbogbodirin Bronze Statue is a revered monument in Ile-Ife,
    Nigeria, commemorating a legendary figure from Yoruba history often identified
    as the second or fourth Ooni (king) of Ife.\n\nHistorical Identity and Longevity\nThe
    \"Methuselah\" of Ife: Obalufon Ogbogbodirin is legendary for his extraordinary
    longevity, with oral traditions claiming he reigned for over 400 years.\n\nThe
    Transfigured King: According to Yoruba mythology, he did not experience a standard
    death but instead transfigured into a metal figurine (or stone in some versions)
    as he aged, eventually becoming a deity.\n\nPatron of the Arts: He is historically
    credited with inventing bronze casting. Under his patronage\u2014and that of
    his son and successor, Obalufon Alayemore\u2014Ife\u2019s bronze, copper, and
    terracotta craftsmanship reached a global peak of refinement between the 12th
    and 14th centuries.\n\nSymbolic and Ritual Significance\nThe statue and the deity
    it represents remain vital to the installation of modern Yoruba kings:\n\nThe
    Aare Crown: Before a new Ooni is crowned, the Aare crown (the most sacred Yoruba
    crown) must be brought to Obalufon\u2019s shrine to be blessed.\n\nPrayers for
    Longevity: Every Ooni following Ogbogbodirin is said to visit his figurine, kneeling
    to pray for a reign as long and stable as his was.\n\nSpiritual Codes: He is
    believed to hold the \"classified spiritual codes\" for a long and prosperous
    reign, making him the patron deity of good governance and the Ogboni society.\n\nModern
    Presence\nA modern, golden-hued bronze statue of Obalufon was commissioned by
    the current Ooni, Oba Adeyeye Enitan Ogunwusi, and erected at the Enuwa Palace.
    This statue serves as a visible reminder of Ife's technological heritage and
    its enduring connection to ancestral power."
