--- !u!114 &2672311288732266439
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 4671609164328154843}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 29b480dc3b7c34901916c4e135caebb1, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::ArtifactController
  artifactData:
    description: "The Obalufon Ogbogbodirin Bronze Statue is a revered monument in
      Ile-Ife, Nigeria, commemorating a legendary figure from Yoruba history often
      identified as the second or fourth Ooni (king) of Ife.\n\nHistorical Identity
      and Longevity\nThe \"Methuselah\" of Ife: Obalufon Ogbogbodirin is legendary
      for his extraordinary longevity, with oral traditions claiming he reigned for
      over 400 years.\n\nThe Transfigured King: According to Yoruba mythology, he
      did not experience a standard death but instead transfigured into a metal figurine
      (or stone in some versions) as he aged, eventually becoming a deity.\n\nPatron
      of the Arts: He is historically credited with inventing bronze casting. Under
      his patronage\u2014and that of his son and successor, Obalufon Alayemore\u2014Ife\u2019s
      bronze, copper, and terracotta craftsmanship reached a global peak of refinement
      between the 12th and 14th centuries.\n\nSymbolic and Ritual Significance\nThe
      statue and the deity it represents remain vital to the installation of modern
      Yoruba kings:\n\nThe Aare Crown: Before a new Ooni is crowned, the Aare crown
      (the most sacred Yoruba crown) must be brought to Obalufon\u2019s shrine to
      be blessed.\n\nPrayers for Longevity: Every Ooni following Ogbogbodirin is
      said to visit his figurine, kneeling to pray for a reign as long and stable
      as his was.\n\nSpiritual Codes: He is believed to hold the \"classified spiritual
      codes\" for a long and prosperous reign, making him the patron deity of good
      governance and the Ogboni society.\n\nModern Presence\nA modern, golden-hued
      bronze statue of Obalufon was commissioned by the current Ooni, Oba Adeyeye
      Enitan Ogunwusi, and erected at the Enuwa Palace. This statue serves as a visible
      reminder of Ife's technological heritage and its enduring connection to ancestral
      power."
